<paragraph id="2D02FD0E76344209B9EB2AD8FCC697B4" blockId="2.[166,1225,441,780]" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">
<keyLead id="964C5E3B76344209B9EB2AD8FCC697B4" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">
3. Metapleuron smooth, impunctate (
<figureCitation id="B586E18B76344209BB082AD8FA7797D0" box="[581,632,672,694]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1769,1791]" captionTargetBox="[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-150@3.[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Clistopyga, ♀. 1, 3, 5, 7 — metapleuron (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi; 2, 4, 6, 8 — ovipositor (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6449473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6449473/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">FIg. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="1FC9211C76344209BBCB2AD8FA9E97D0" box="[646,657,672,694]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">5</emphasis>
). Hind femur entirely red. Ovipositor weakly apically upcurved, the length is about 1.4–1.5 × length of hind tibia (
<figureCitation id="B586E18B76344209BA5A2AC4FB4797B4" box="[791,840,700,722]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1769,1791]" captionTargetBox="[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-150@3.[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Clistopyga, ♀. 1, 3, 5, 7 — metapleuron (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi; 2, 4, 6, 8 — ovipositor (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6449473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6449473/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">FIg. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="1FC9211C76344209BA1E2AC4FB5197B4" box="[851,862,700,722]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">6</emphasis>
). ...................................... 
<taxonomicName id="EABD868D76344209BD042AC4FCC697B4" authorityName="Provancher" authorityYear="1880" box="[1097,1225,700,722]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Clistopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis id="1FC9211C76344209BD042AC4FCC697B4" box="[1097,1225,700,722]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">C. canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D02FD0E76344209B9EB2AA1FCC7966A" blockId="2.[166,1225,441,780]" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">
<keyLead id="964C5E3B76344209B9EB2AA1FCC7966A" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">
— Metapleuron granulate (
<figureCitation id="B586E18B76344209B8942AA1FA049789" box="[473,523,729,751]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1769,1791]" captionTargetBox="[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-150@3.[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Clistopyga, ♀. 1, 3, 5, 7 — metapleuron (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi; 2, 4, 6, 8 — ovipositor (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6449473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6449473/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">FIg. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="1FC9211C76344209BB5A2AA1FA2D9789" box="[535,546,729,751]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">7</emphasis>
). Hind femur red, apically fuscous. Ovipositor strongly uniformly upcurved, the length is about 1.2 × length of hind tibia (
<figureCitation id="B586E18B76344209BBA32A8EFB10966A" box="[750,799,758,780]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1769,1791]" captionTargetBox="[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-150@3.[276,1153,630,1748]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Clistopyga, ♀. 1, 3, 5, 7 — metapleuron (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi; 2, 4, 6, 8 — ovipositor (lateral view): 1 — C. incitator; 3 — C. rufator; 5 — C. canadensis; 7 — C. sziladyi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6449473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6449473/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">FIg. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="1FC9211C76344209BA672A8EFB3A966A" box="[810,821,758,780]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="369">8</emphasis>
). ................................................... 
